\par }{\cf5 4. PropertyAccessTimeout
\par }{\tab Name:\tab \tab PropertyAccessTimeout
\par \tab Type:\tab \tab Long
\par \tab Access:\tab \tab Read / Write
\par \tab Usage:\tab \tab Used to read or write the timeout value used when synchronously accessing a 
\par }\pard \fi720\li1440\nowidctlpar\adjustright {property. The timeout is expressed in milliseconds. This unique property is used 
\par for *all* the synchronous property accesses being done in the control.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\tab Example:\tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab }{\cf2 Dim ci As ChatItems
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab MsChatPr1.PropertyAccessTimeout = 10000}{\tab \lquote  10 seconds
\par \tab \tab \tab }{\cf2 Set ci = MsChatPr1.ChannelProperty(\ldblquote MaxMemberCount\rdblquote , \ldblquote #MyRoom\rdblquote )}{
\par \tab \tab \tab \lquote \'85 use ci
\par \tab \tab \tab }{\cf2 Set ci = MsChatPr1.Channels(2).MemberProperty(\ldblquote Identity\rdblquote , \ldblquote Mila\rdblquote )}{
\par \tab \tab \tab \lquote \'85 use ci
\par \tab \tab \tab }{\cf2 Set ci = Nothing}{
\par 
\par \tab Notes:\tab \tab If a timeout condition occurs when trying to synchronously access a property an 
\par }\pard \fi720\li1440\nowidctlpar\adjustright {error is returned. An OnChannelProperty, OnServerProperty,
\par OnMemberProperty or OnUserProperty event might be fired after a timeout 
\par error occurs. This event exposes the property that could be accessed on time.
\par 
\par }{\cf2 Dim ci As ChatItems
\par 
\par MsChatPr1.PropertyAccessTimeout = 10}{\tab \lquote  10 milliseconds
\par }{\cf2 Set ci = MsChatPr1.ChannelProperty(\ldblquote MaxMemberCount\rdblquote , \ldblquote #MyRoom\rdblquote )}{
\par \lquote }{\lang1024 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 224 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f14\fs20}}}{ an error is thrown
\par \lquote }{\lang1024 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 224 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f14\fs20}}}{ an OnChannelProperty(Nothing, ChannelItems) event is fired later on, 
\par where ChannelItems exposes the MaxMemberCount property and all the other 
\par known properties.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cf5 \page 5. ProcessProtocolMessages
\par }{\tab Name:\tab \tab ProcessProtocolMessages
\par \tab Type:\tab \tab Boolean
\par \tab Access:\tab \tab Read / Write
\par \tab Usage:\tab \tab Determines whether or not the OnProtocolMessage event is fired for each 
\par }\pard \fi720\li1440\nowidctlpar\adjustright {incoming server message.
\par When ProcessProtocolMessages is set to True, the incoming server messages 
\par are immediatelly treated internally and exposed via some event. The 
\par OnProtocolMessage event is only fired when the incoming server message can 
\par not be properly interpreted by the control.
\par However when ProcessProtocolMessages is set to False, the control first 
\par exposes the incoming server messages via the 
\par OnProtocolMessage(MessagePrefix, MessageCommand, MessageParameters, 
\par EnableDefault) event.
\par In the OnProtocolMessage event handler the OCX user can set the 
\par }\pard \li2160\nowidctlpar\adjustright {EnableDefault parameter to True or False. The param is set to True by default. 
\par If set to True, the control treats the incoming server message normally and fires the usual event. If set the False however, the control won\rquote t treat the message internally.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {\tab Tip:\tab \tab Only experts should set the ProcessProtocolMessages property to False. If the 
\par }\pard \fi720\li1440\nowidctlpar\adjustright {incoming messages are not treated internally by the control, it might end up in 
\par an unstable state. This mode had to be handled with extrem caution.
\par 
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\adjustright {
\par \tab Example:
\par \tab \tab \tab }{\cf2 MsChatPr1.ProcessProtocolMessages = False}{
\par }{\cf5 
\par 
